# Agile Epics

## Definition

An epic is a large body of work that delivers a significant business capability. It can be broken down into features and user stories.

## Epic Structure

Every epic document must include:

| Section | Content |
|---------|---------|
| **Title & ID** | `EPIC-NNN: Descriptive Title` |
| **Owner** | Person accountable for the epic |
| **Business Value** | Why this matters to the business (measurable) |
| **Target Users** | Who benefits from this epic |
| **Problem Statement** | What problem does this solve |
| **Success Criteria** | How do we know the epic is done (measurable KPIs) |
| **Scope** | In scope / out of scope boundaries |
| **Key Features** | 3-7 high-level features (each becomes a feature doc) |
| **Dependencies** | External teams, systems, or decisions blocking this |
| **Risks & Assumptions** | Known risks and assumptions made |
| **Timeline** | Target quarter/sprint range |

## Constraints

- Each epic should be completable within 1-3 months
- Limit to 3-7 features per epic; split larger epics
- Success criteria must be measurable (numbers, percentages, time targets)
- Review epics at least once per sprint for scope and priority changes

## Breakdown Pattern

```
Epic (1-3 months)
├── Feature 1 (1-3 sprints)
│   ├── User Story 1.1 (1-3 days)
│   ├── User Story 1.2
│   └── User Story 1.3
├── Feature 2
│   ├── User Story 2.1
│   └── User Story 2.2
└── Feature 3
    └── User Story 3.1
```

